    </div>
  </section>

  <div class="post-body-wrap">
    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>An <strong>email preheader</strong> is the short preview text displayed next to or below the subject line in most email clients. It acts as a secondary subject line — a second bite at convincing someone to open. When left unset, clients pull random body text instead, which almost always hurts open rates.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Ideal length</div>
            <div class="tms-value">40–90 characters</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Email Marketing</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Open rate impact</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Up to +40%</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Most marketers spend 80% of their email effort on the body and forget the two lines that decide whether anyone reads it — the subject line and the preheader. Getting both right is the lowest-effort, highest-return move in an email programme.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is an email preheader?</h2>
        <p>The preheader (also called preview text or the Johnson Box in direct mail tradition) is the snippet of text that email clients show in the inbox view before a recipient opens the message. It appears after the sender name and subject line, typically in a lighter grey font.</p>
        <p>Every major email client renders it differently:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Gmail (desktop):</strong> Shows up to 90 characters after the subject line on the same row</li>
          <li><strong>Apple Mail (iOS):</strong> Shows 2 lines of preview beneath the subject, roughly 75-100 characters</li>
          <li><strong>Outlook (desktop):</strong> Shows a single preview line, around 35-55 characters</li>
          <li><strong>Gmail (mobile):</strong> Shows approximately 30-55 characters depending on screen size</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Because most opens now happen on mobile, the safe working length is <strong>40-55 characters</strong> for guaranteed visibility, with up to 90 characters for clients that show more.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">How email clients pull preheader text</div>
          <p>If you do not set a preheader explicitly, email clients read the first visible text in your HTML — which is frequently "View this email in your browser," your unsubscribe footer, or an ALT tag. These destroy open rates. Always set preheader text intentionally.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why email preheaders matter for open rates</h2>
        <p>The inbox is a conversion funnel of its own. Before anyone reads your email, they decide whether to open it based on three signals: sender name, subject line, and preheader. Neglecting any one of them leaves open-rate points on the table.</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>It extends the subject line's sell.</strong> A subject line has 6-10 words. The preheader doubles that real estate. Together they can set context, tease a benefit, and resolve urgency — things no subject line alone can do.</li>
          <li><strong>It prevents embarrassing fallbacks.</strong> Without an intentional preheader, your first body text becomes the preview. "Hi [First Name]," or "ALT: hero-image" appearing in inboxes is common and immediately damages credibility.</li>
          <li><strong>It directly lifts open rates.</strong> Optimised preheaders have driven open rate increases of 20-40% in documented split tests. A 1-percentage-point open rate improvement across 10,000 subscribers means 100 more opens per send.</li>
          <li><strong>It works for every email type.</strong> Newsletters, promotional emails, transactional messages, drip sequences — every email benefits from a thoughtful preheader.</li>
          <li><strong>It is almost zero extra work.</strong> Writing a good preheader takes under 5 minutes. The ROI per minute is higher than almost any other email optimization.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How email preheaders work technically</h2>
        <p>Preheader text is injected into the HTML of your email using a hidden <code>span</code> element placed immediately after the opening <code>body</code> tag, before any visible content. Most email service providers expose a dedicated "Preview text" field in their editor that handles this automatically.</p>

        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment">&lt;!-- How preheader is coded in email HTML --&gt;</span><br>
          &lt;body&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;span style="display:none;max-height:0px;overflow:hidden;"&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-new">Your preheader text goes here — 40 to 90 characters</span><br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;/span&gt;<br>
          &nbsp;&nbsp;<span class="uf-comment">&lt;!-- visible email content starts below --&gt;</span><br>
          &lt;/body&gt;
        </div>

        <p>The hidden span is styled to be invisible in the email body but readable by inbox preview parsers. Some ESPs also add filler characters after the text to prevent the email body from bleeding into the preview.</p>

