        <h2 id="examples">Real email preheader examples</h2>
        <p>Three before-and-after examples that show how a weak preheader becomes one that drives opens.</p>

        <h3>1. E-commerce promotional email</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-label">Subject:</span> <span class="uf-old">Summer sale is here!</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Weak preheader:</span> <span class="uf-old">View this email in your browser</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-label">Subject:</span> <span class="uf-new">Summer sale is here!</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Strong preheader:</span> <span class="uf-new">30% off everything — ends Sunday at midnight</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. B2B newsletter</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-label">Subject:</span> <span class="uf-old">The Weekly SEO Brief</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Weak preheader:</span> <span class="uf-old">Hi [First Name], hope you're doing well...</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-label">Subject:</span> <span class="uf-new">The Weekly SEO Brief</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Strong preheader:</span> <span class="uf-new">Google's core update winners — and the pattern behind them</span>
        </div>

        <h3>3. SaaS abandoned trial email</h3>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-label">Subject:</span> <span class="uf-old">Don't lose your progress</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Weak preheader:</span> <span class="uf-old">You haven't logged in yet</span><br>
          <br>
          <span class="uf-label">Subject:</span> <span class="uf-new">Don't lose your progress</span><br>
          <span class="uf-label">Strong preheader:</span> <span class="uf-new">Your 14-day trial ends in 3 days — your data stays for 30 more</span>
        </div>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Email preheader vs subject line — how they work together</h2>
        <p>The subject line and preheader are two parts of the same open-rate argument. They should never repeat each other.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Subject line</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>States the core hook or promise</li>
              <li>6-10 words maximum for mobile</li>
              <li>Gets read first — sets the frame</li>
              <li>Optimise for curiosity or urgency</li>
              <li>Test emoji vs no-emoji for your list</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Preheader</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Extends or adds a second angle</li>
              <li>40-90 characters — more room to sell</li>
              <li>Read second — closes the argument</li>
              <li>Optimise for specificity and detail</li>
              <li>Add numbers, deadlines, social proof</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">6 best practices for email preheaders</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Never repeat the subject line.</strong> It wastes the real estate. The preheader should add new information — a deadline, a statistic, a secondary benefit.</li>
          <li><strong>Front-load the key phrase.</strong> Mobile clients truncate at 30-55 characters. Put the word that matters most in the first 5 words.</li>
          <li><strong>Use numbers whenever possible.</strong> "Save 30% — ends Sunday" outperforms "Big savings this weekend" every time. Numbers are specific; specificity earns trust.</li>
          <li><strong>Match the email tone.</strong> A playful welcome email deserves a playful preheader. A transactional update needs a factual one. Mismatched tone confuses readers.</li>
          <li><strong>A/B test every send you can.</strong> Split-test preheader variants at least once per quarter. Even a 2% open rate lift compounds substantially over a year.</li>
          <li><strong>Include a filler block for long emails.</strong> Add invisible whitespace characters after your preheader to prevent body copy bleeding into the preview area.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — treating the preheader as a summary</div>
          <p>The preheader is not a summary of the email. Summarising what is inside removes all reason to open. Use it to create forward momentum — give a hint, not the full picture. "3 things you're getting wrong about preheaders" beats "In this email: preheader tips" every time.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common email preheader mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Leaving it blank</strong> — forces the client to pull random body text, frequently "View this email in your browser"</li>
          <li><strong>Repeating the subject line verbatim</strong> — doubles the subject line word count in the preview but adds zero new value</li>
          <li><strong>Writing more than 90 characters</strong> — extra text gets cut and you risk mid-sentence truncation</li>
          <li><strong>Using vague language</strong> — "Great content inside!" tells the reader nothing and earns no opens</li>
          <li><strong>Using spam trigger words</strong> — ALL CAPS or excessive exclamation marks in preheaders contribute to spam filter scoring</li>
          <li><strong>Not testing across email clients</strong> — Gmail and Apple Mail render previews differently; use Litmus or Email on Acid before major sends</li>
        </ul>

